It depends. If it's a bigger team than you, talk them up for sure because you want them to not be motivated. Mine right now can't handle any kind of pressure and doesn't get complacent much so I project confidence. It's basically just an extension of the team talk that the other team can hear too. It really depends on your situation and the other team's. If the other manager compliments me I usually call it condescending. If I have a good streak going against another team/manager I ALWAYS use the one that says the other team has the pressure to end it. If I have a losing streak vs them the one that sucks the Manager's dick (he's one of the best managers in the game and that's a level I've yet to reach) seems to work often enough. posts.name: Anonymous

>>128081442
Ah you'll get there. One thing I'll say is don't be afraid to tweak the tactics during the match if something looks bad. Man mark a guy specifically, move the D line, etc. You can make most tactics work just by adjusting in game and fixing what looks dangerous. Also until you meme your way into the CL it's kind of difficult to improve the squad by enough to compete with the top 4 in a match consistently because the best options won't want to sign with you. I took my team up from serie C without replacing any of my starters until serie A and I'm just now getting competitive with Milan/Juventus after like 5 seasons of spending ~30 million a year, and england is even harder in my opinion.

Still, it could be your tactics if you have god tier players. the midfield combo for instance sounds a little conservative. DLP and AP are a little redundant. I like an AMC as an AM-A with decent shooting and playmaking abilities so it gives you more of a dual threat. I run the same formation and I have the wingers, AMC, and striker all with attack duties, in front of a BWM and a BBM. Also, this year you really need to make sure the wingers track back to cover the other team's fullbacks, especially against strong teams, so that could be an issue too with that formation. During the match if I see their fullbacks getting so far forward that my wingers abandon them, I set them to specifically mark that player by name (the only way they'll actually stay with them all the way to the byline)

>>128111308
Other curious thing is there is an alternative spelling of the name with an ä instead of an a which is mostly just found in Estonia, but also in Switzerland. My relatives came from Switzerland where both spellings exist roughly equally, even though an Italian-Swiss name (which is what we assumed it was) wouldn't use the ä. So it seems plausible that some Estonians with that name moved to Switzerland, some dropped the ä to an a which is where my family name comes from, ergo I am potentially Estonian.

The reason this is a particularly odd is that I went all around Europe to most of the countries and Estonia was my favourite, I got there and kind of realized that it was my home, I looked into ways I could move there but it was not feasible. But I always somehow felt that is the place I am supposed to be. Obviously this was before I knew about the name thing, I only just found that out now.

>Draw = 1pt
>Loss = 0pt
>GD is the decider

Current system
>Win = 3pts
>Draw = 1pt
>Loss = 0pt
>GD is the decider

New system
>Win = 6(+GD)pts, max cap 9
>Draw/Loss = 3(-GD)pts, min cap 0
>GS is the decider

>encourages more attacking play by giving additional points for a +2 or +3 winning margin
>encourages teams who are drawing late in the game to take more risks to get the win, since losing by just 1 goal doesn't completely wipe out all your points
>teams that grind out 1-0 wins will finish below teams that absolute batter others
>using goals scored instead of goal difference as the decider encourages high scoring matches
>it also makes a distinction between shitters and absolute shitters by factoring in the severity of losses
>instead of only dominant teams only getting what is effectively 1 bonus point at the end of the season, the difference between winning every game 1-0 and winning every game 3-0 comes with a 28% point bonus

posts.com:
'Public' Park Barbecue Rules

My kitchen has a four burner electric stove which costs a fortune to run, I cook dinner every night and very rarely go out so it's a large chunk of my electricity bill.

I live in a nice area and I'm lucky enough to have the back fence of my house facing onto a public park.

Within a few meters of my fence there is one of those free public barbecues, the electric kind that has a push button and turns off on its own after a while.

Since I moved here almost 2 years ago, I have used my own stove probably once or twice when it's been incredibly cold outside.

I have a little cart I fill with ingredients and wheel over to the public barbecue most nights. I also use it as a hotplate to boil water for dishwashing (and occasionally for a bath - all water from the nearby public tap of course). I estimate I am saving over $300 a year by doing this (electricity alone).

Here's where things get a little interesting. My next door neighbours whom I have barely spoken to since I moved in have started to pay a lot of attention to my use of the barbecue. It started when they had some friends over and wanted to use it for some sausages after I had already started a risotto. They were quite rude about it and it escalated to an all out screaming match. Thankfully they backed down before things got physical and ever since I have kept my phone on record when they come near.

Today I received a letter from my landlord explaining that I may be in breach of my lease and detailing a number of complaints he has received from both my neighbours and the council. The council is demanding that I stop using the 'public' barbecue.

The neighbours also claim I have been stealing their electricity and I am being threatened with eviction because of it. Once or twice I have plugged an extension cord into an outlet that is near their pool equipment but I only did so to power a lamp and a blender and I didn't even have to go over their fence to reach it.
